    <definition xml:id="def-x_intercept">
      <title><m>x</m>-intercept</title>
      <statement>
	<p>
	  A <xref ref="def-solution" text="title"/> of the form <m>(x,0)</m> is called an <term><m>x</m>-intercept</term>.
	  <idx>
	    <h>Equation</h>
	    <h><m>x</m>-intercept</h>
	  </idx>
	</p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    
    <example component="web">
      <p>
	The graph of the equation <m>y = 2x - 2</m> is shown below.
	The <m>y</m>-intercept occurs when <m>x = 0</m> and
	<md>
	  <mrow>y \amp = 2(0) -2 \amp\amp \text{Simplify}</mrow>
	  <mrow>y \amp = -2.</mrow>
	</md>
	The <m>x</m>-intercept occurs when <m>y = 0</m> and
	<md>
	  <mrow>0 \amp = 2x - 2 \amp\amp \text{Add}\ 2\ \text{to both sides}</mrow>
	  <mrow>2 \amp = 2x \amp\amp \text{Divide both sides by}\ 2</mrow>
	  <mrow>1 \amp = x \amp\amp \text{Swap sides}</mrow>
	  <mrow>x \amp = 1.</mrow>
	</md>
	This tells us, as ordered pairs, the <m>x</m>-intercept occurs at <m>(1,0)</m> and the <m>y</m>-intercept occurs at <m>(0,-2)</m>.
	In general, every point on this line has coordinates of the form <m>(x,2x - 2)</m>, where <m>x</m> can be any real number we choose.
      </p>
      <figure>
	<caption>The graph of the equation <m>y = 2x - 2</m>.</caption>
	<image>
	  <latex-image>
	    <xi:include parse="text" href="tex/y_2x-2-with_points.tex"/>
	  </latex-image>
	</image>
      </figure>
    </example>

